{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958041801/0233.xml":{"full_text":"s\n\u00ab\u20acDERATO,\nOe\nA\nO I\nz\nG\nAFL 22\u2014CIO\nI Z\n9\nS\nO,\nMREC\nDuSTRIAL\n.0\nCP\n/s\n\nOfficial Newspaper Of\nToledo Industrial\nUnion Council\nTOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nSinse\n\u2022o\net y. s\nN L Y L A BIC\nNEWSPAPER\n#8\n4,\nS\nw\nC* -oogew K.R**\n\nrsrove\nMwyr\ns. \u2018*9yer*\nVOL. 16, NO. 16\nPublished By Organized Labor\n425 Winthrop St., Toledo, Ome\nf\nK.8<54/ F2229\ns si9w\nP.U B LISiH E D\nEVER\nWJ\nEEK\nIN\nTOLEDO\n,*%Y*\n246\n4\n4. q\n9\nSkS8.\ntw\nw <4: wonbkcok\nwkel\n\nR&Skni2* i\nTOLEDO, OHIO, FRIDAY, APRIL 18, 1958\nPAnYSee RUB co.\nA\nTOLEDO\no\nOf Over 31,000 Subscribers\nFrom 120 Area Plants\nMail Delivered To Homes\nInquiring\nReporter\n\"What kind of articles or features do you like\nto read in the Union Journal?**\nPaczkowski\nCampbell\ny\nIrving Paczkowski, 1202 Te\ncumseh: \u201cI read the sports page\nand our column first and then\ntry to follow what is going on in\nthe different plants. I would like\nto see the Journal have more\narticles on golf especially the\nindustrial league.\"\nMinor Campbell, 115 8 Lin\ncoln: \u201cI read the whole paper to\nkeep informed on all that is go\ning on. It is an interesting paper\nand think that all who can\nshould read it even if they don\u2019t\nbelong to a union. In this way\ni they can get our view on matters\nof importance. I would like to\nsee the Journal have some arti\ncles on fishing because it is a\nsport in which many of us are\ninterested.\"\nRischman\nMcMilleh\n\nBetty Rischman, 5329 Fortune:\n\u201cI like to read the articles that\naffect us workers such as the\n\u201cRight to Work Bill.\" When we\nknow what it is all about we\nknow how to vote. The Journal\nis a very good publication and\nI don\u2019t know of anything that\ncould be done to improve it.\"\nJulia McMilleh, 2336 Berdan:\n\u201cFirst' of all I read our shop\ncolumn and look at all the pic\ntures. Then I read the ads to see\nwhat kind of bargains I can get.\nI wish the Journal had a help\nwanted section for those who are\nunemployed.\u201d\nKnecht\nF\nDean\nRobert Knecht, 6158 Bonsels:\n\u201cI read the whole paper and es\nSurplus Foods To Needy Being Considered\nBy BARROW LYONS\nIndependent Features\nWASHINGTON\u2014P Ians for\nmaking surplus foods available\nin far larger quantities to needy\nand undernourished persons are\nagain becoming a focus of at\ntention here. They offer multi\nple advantages in the public in\nterest.\nUnder these plans millions of\npersons now unable to buy suf\n$1 ficient food to keep healthy\nwould be helped. At the same\ntime the farmer would be aided\nby massive purchases\u2019 of over\nstocked farm commodities, and\nby the creation of new demand\nfor meats, fruits and fresh vege\ntables to round out presently in\nadequate diets.\nThe whole economy would get\na shot in the arm through the\nexpansion of purchasing power\nof the low-income groups, and\nimprovement of the farmer's eco\nnomic position.\nThe cost to federal and local\ngovernments would be consid\nerable, but almost certainly less\nthan the cost of any of the pro\ngrams for building -roads,\nschools, housing, or missiles. And\nthe gains in health and economic\nproductivity unquestionably\npecially our shop column. The\ninformation I get from my chair\nman plus what I read keeps me\nwell informed. I would like the\nJournal to have articles on gar\ndening in which I am interest\ned.\"\nCharles Dean, 4015 Nebraska:\n\"I read almost all of the paper\nabout the union and its activity.\nI sometimes miss the editorial\ncolumn but not very often. I al\nways read the shop columns to\nsee what is going on at the other\nplants.\"\nI\nLowery\nrw\nGochik\nMildred Lowery, 1922 Wash-\nington: \u201cFirst of all of course I!\nread our shop column and then\nabout the other plants, unem\nployment and the various bills\nthat are to be voted on. I also\n1 enjoy the pictures and sport sec-|\ntion which are very good. I can't,\n{think of anything else I would\nI like to see in the paper.\" 1\nI\nErnest Gochik, 3716 Berkley:\n\"I read most of the paper and'\nlook at all the pictures because]\nI think our paper is one of the!\n{most interesting and informative\npapers of all labor newspapers.\nI believe more people should\nread editorial and political news\nso that they will be better in-!\nformed and know how to vote\nand know how to answer some\nof the questions that non-union\npeople ask.\u201d\nI\nI\n\u2022I\nt\nA-LUnit Meets\nSaturday to Act\nOn 1958 Contract\nNew contract proposals to\nbe presented to management\nwill be acted on by members\nof the Local 12 Electric Auto-\nLite Unit at a meeting Satur-\n1 day (April 19) at 11:30 a.m.\nin Scott High School audi\ntorium.\nThe Executive Shop Com\nmittee urged all members\nemployed and laid-off to\nattend and to use \u201ctheir demo\ncratic right to accept or reject\u201d\nthe proposals.\nThe proposals were drafted\nby the Executive Shop Com\nmittee and steward body and\nwill be given to management\nafter they are ratified by the\nmembers.\n0000111110111%%%\nwould be enormous, even if not\nsusceptible of accurate measure\nment.\nThe Anfusio Bill\nThe first plan to get the at\ntention of Congress is that em\nbodied in a bill introduced by.\nRep. Victor L. Anfusio (D-N.Y.)j\ncalling for the free distribution\nof food stamps to needy persons.\nIt comes up for hearings this,\nweek before the Consumer Study\nSubcommittee of the House Com-!\nmittee on Agriculture, of which\nAnfusio is chairman.\n1\nThe Anfusio Bill is a straight\nstamp distribution measure\nmuch like the plan instituted by\nthe Surplus Marketing Adminis\ntration under Milo Perkins in\n1942, which was abolished the\nfollowing year.\nIt is a short bill which would\nlimit the value of foods distrib\nuted in any calendar year to one\nbillion dollars. Distribution of\nfood stamps would be to states\nand local goverhments under the\ndirection of the Secretary of Ag\nriculture. i\nThe stamps would constitute\na special kind of money with\nwhich the needy persons to,\nr'' i\n\u201ds\nf\nts\n\u2014omonomn,\"\"**.\n6.23\n\n1 C\nFA\n\nth.e\nChart Shows Insured Unemployment Claims in U. S. I\nA state by state breakdown of the number\nof unemployment compensation claims is\nshown in this chart prepared by the AFL\nCIO. The chart was used in Congressional\nhearings held to extend benefits. From\nleft are Social Security Director Nelson\nCruikshank, Kitty Ellickson, assistant di\nrector, and Leonard Lesser, director of\nsocial security activities for the AFL-CIO\nIndustrial Union Dept.\nThis Week in City Council:\nCzelusta Blasts Times Editor\nFor Making False Statements9\nShorter Week\nFor Police\nRecommended\nAlthough the police asked for\na speedup of schedule placing\nthem on a 40-hour week. Coun\ncil decided Monday to institute.\na 44-hour week for policemen by\nJan. 1, 1959 and a reduction to\n40 hours the following Jan. 1.\nThe change* will be made with\nout a cut in pay.\nMayor Yager reported that 38\nmore men will be needed when\npolice go on a 44-hour week and\nit will cost $45,000 to train them.\nAnother $50,000 will be needed\nto train the recruits in the shift,\nto 40 weeks.\nCost of a 44-hour week for\npolice the first year will be\n$401,000, Council was told, and\nthe police budget will increase\nby $441,000 when the change is\nmade to a 40-hour week.\nI\nLeland Stipes, a spokesman,\nfor the Fraternal Order of Po\nlice, in asking for a speedup in,\nthe change to a shorter week,\ndeclared that policemen were\npromised a 40-hour week when\nthe payroll income tax went into\neffect.\nA survey made of five Toledo\nplants, he said, showed that they\nwere paying their guards more\nthan the city was paying its\npolicemen. He also declared that!\nsince 1941 the city had increased\nin population and area but the\nsize of the police force remained\nthe same.\nwhom they were given by local\nagencies buy foods held by the\nAgriculture Department to be in\nsurplus.\nThe Aiken Proposal\nMuch more detailed is the\nplan of Senator George D. Aik\nen (R-Vt.) which was introduced\nfirst a few weeks after the old\nStamp Plan was abolished in\n1943, and from which Congress\nhas shied away ever since.\nBoth the Aiken bill and the\nProxmire measure seek to assure\na well balanced diet for needy\npersons, but the Aiken bill is\nmuch more specific as to what\nthey would be given by way of\nfresh meats, fruit and vegetables.\nOutside the Congress the al\nlotmen plan now has important\ncitizen support. The Agricultural\nCommittee of the National Plan\nning Association consisting of 21\nprominent business men, econo\nmists, and editors, has endorsed\na plan like the Aiken proposal.\nLauren K. Soth, editorial page\neditor of the Des Moines Regis-!\nter Tribune, is chairman of\nthis committee.\nIf the economic recession con\ntinues to deepen, it is almost\ncertain that the Food Allotment\nPlan will receive serious con\nsideration at this session of Con\nA bitter attack on Toledo Times editor George Benson\nby Vice Mayor Ollie Czelusta and attempts by another\ncouncilman to have Mr. Czelusta\u2019s remarks stricken from\nthe record marred City Council\u2019s usual peaceful sessions\nMonday.\nVice Mayor Czelusta ac\ncused the Times editor of\nhurling \u201cfalse statements\u201d\nand \u201cembarking on a rhetorical'\nrabble rousing binge\u201d aimed at.\nar.ousing a peaceful public\nI\nMr. Czelusta said he had not\nchanged his position on a dog\nleach ordinance and explained\nthat he had rejected a report by\nCity Manager Rink because her\nwasn\u2019t satisfied with it.\nAsserting that a Toledo Times\neditorial was \u201call without jus\ntification or evidence\u201d he said\nthat the editor was \"not con\ncerned with the truth.\" I\nMr. Czelusta charged that the\nBenson editorial questioned the\nintegrity of the Councilmen and\npointed out the Times editor \u201chas\nthe obligation of propelling the\ntruth to the people\u201d and that he\ndoesn\u2019t seem to be concerned\u201d\nabout it.\nTo make his position clear, Mr.\nCzelusta requested the law de\npartment to bring in an ordi\nnance on dog control which\nwould be effective and could be\nenforced.\nI\nCouncilman Max Reddish took\nexception to the Vice Mayor's\nremarks and moved that they!\nbe stricken from the record.\nI\nMayor John W. Yager pointed\nout that no Councilman in his\nrecollections had ever asked that\nanother's remarks be stricken.\nCouncilman Michael Damas!\nsided with the Vice Mayor in\ngress;\nbut\nif\nbusiness\nshows!\nmarked improvement, it could\neasily die on the vine. I\nImportance Made Clear\nFood, of course, ranks as the.\ngreatest necessity of families\nwith low income. Data present-!\ned by the Conference on Eco\nnomic Progress in its report en\ntitled \u201cConsumption Key To\nFull Prosperity\u201d showed that\nwage earners with income under\n$2,000 yearly spend about 70\npercent of them on food, and.\nbetween\nthose with\nincomes\n$3,000 and $4,000 spend 41 per\ncent on food.\nBoth the Proxmire and Aiken\n11 _.1_.2 e_1_.\nbills would permit food coupons\nto be issued to low-income fam\nilies up to only 40 percent of,\nthe total income of such families,1\nhowever. This suggests the in\nadequacy of these measures in\nfulfilling their purposes of sup\nplying an-adequate diet to many\nfamilies of very low income. And\nunder both bills the recipient of\nthe stamps would pay in cash\nfor them not less than 25 per\ncent of their face value.\nObviously these is a great and\ngrowing need No one will pre\ndict whether the present Con\ngress will move to meet it\u2014but\npressures are increasing.\ncontending that the charges in\nthe Times editorial were \u201cun\nfair\" and said Mr. Czelusta was\n\"absolutely correct.\u201d\nCouncilman Joseph Scalzo\nnoted that \u201cMr. Benson has a\n.right to say what he wants and\n1 Councilmen should have the\nright to the same privilege.\"\n\u201cIt would establish a bad\nprecedent to strike remarks by\nany Councilman,\u201d J. B. Simmons,\nJr., pointed out.\nI Council then moved to table\nthe Reddish resolution by a vote\nof 7 to 2. Only Councilman Har\nold Wagner sided with Mr. Red\ndish.\nPublic Works\nAre Readied\nTo Make Jobs\nCouncil's public works com\nmittee, headed by Vice Mayor\nOllie Czelusta, approved 10\nstreet improvement projects that\ncould be undertaken speedily\nwhen Federal and state funds\nwere made available.\nThe\ncommittee was given the\ngo-ahead sign by Council to\nprepare public works projects\nand have them ready when\nfunds became available. Coun\ncil had acted upon a request by\nthe UAW Educational League\nin an effort to get the jobless\nback to work.\nWilliam Gross, service direc\ntor, told the committee that\nwork could begin on these pro\njects quickly if the Federal Gov\nernment released the funds. To\nqualify, he said, the projects\nwould have to be under con\ntract by Dec. 1.\nThe biggest project calls for\n[widening Monroe St. from 36\nfeet to 54 feet from Ten Mile\nCreek to Central Ave., with the\nFederal Government paying\ntwo-thirds the cost, and the\ncunty and city splitting the re\nmainder.\nAmong other resurfacing jobs\nthat could be started on, Mr.\nGross said, were resurfacing\nAnthony Wayne Trail, Cherry\nSt. from Summit to Detroit;\nEast Broadway from Starr Ave.\nto the Wood County line; Miami\nSt. from Fassett to the Wood\nCounty line and Fassett from\nMiami to Oak Sts.\nAnother needed work cited by\nthe service director were over\npasses at York St. over the\nNickel\u2019Plate and Toledo Termi\nnal railroads.\n_a*a*a*=*************a*a****aAA.\nVVVUUUweUUwVVVVVVVUUUVUVVVVVU\nCredit Unions\u2019 Role\nOn \u2018Voice of Labor\u2019\n\u201cWhat credit unions can do\nfor workers\u201d will be discussed\nby a representative of the\nCredit Unions National As\nsociation on \u201cThe Voice of La\nbor\u201d TV program over WSPD\nTV this Sunday at noon.\nWMWMWM\nEconomy Continues Slide\nAs Jobless Hits New High\nThe nation\u2019s economy con\ntinued its downward slide in\nMarch as the worst recession\nsince the end of World War\nII produced new record un\nunemployment figures.\nGovernment reports indicated\nat least 25,000 were added to\nthe jobless rolls, a sharp reversal\nof the normal drop of 200,000\nin unemployment in mid-March.\nEmployment increased 323.000\nfrom mid-February to m i d\nMarch in contrast with a normal\nincrease of about 500,000 at the\nstart of the spring season.\nNew Postwar High\nThe result: the rate of unem-i\nployment rose from 6.7 percent\nto 7 percent, a new postwar high.\nAFL-CIO George Meany\nsaid the figures in the joint\nreport of the Labor and Com\nmerce Depts, \u201cindicate a con\ntinued deepening of the reces\nsion. There is nothing\nto indicate that the recession\nhas hit bottom, let alone any\nsign of a pick-up.\u201d\nHe added: \u201cThere is nothing'\nthat we in the AFL-CIO would\nwelcome more than an end to\nthis recession. But facts are facts'\nand there isn't a single ray of\nsunshine\u201d in the report.\n\u201cThe only way to change the\nsituation is for the government\nto act now. Optimistic press re\nleases won't end this recession\nbut legislation can.\u201d\nThe White House, however,\nclaimed that the figures indicat\ned a \u201cslowing up of the decline,\u201d\nand Labor Sec. Mitchell, in a\nstatement for the newsreels,\ni termed the figures \"encourag\ning\u201d and said that the nation's\neconomy is \u201cbasically sound.\u201d\nFactory Employment Dips\n1\nThe 323,000 rise in employ\nment was concentrated in farm\nlabor and construction contrast\ning with the 200,000 drop in\nmanufacturing, a much greater\nthan seasonal decline.\nJobs in manufacturing were\ndown by 1.5 million from a\nyear ago and non-farm em\nployment was 1,749,000 below\nthe March 1957 figures.\nThe government report showed\nalso that:\nt\nThe number of persons out\nof work 15 weeks or longer rose\nsharply by 300,000 to a postwar\nrecord of 1,446,000.\nThe number of persons\nworking a short work week was\nup 200,000 to 2,290,000. The av\ni erage factory work week was\nunchanged from February at\n38.5 hours and weekly wages av\neraged about the same as the\npreceding month but were down\n$1.35 from a year ago.\nState insured unemploy\nment showed a continued in\nChambers\nUnion Busting\nLaw Draws More Opposition\nAn employers\u2019 association and a Cleveland minister\nhave added their voices to the growing list of groups and\npersons who have taken public stands against a proposed\n\u201cright-to-work\u201d law for Ohio.\nThe latest organization to condemn the \u201cright-to-work\u201d\nI\n'campaign of the Ohio Cham\nber is the Ohio State Lathing\nand Plastering Contractors\u2019;\nAssociation. I\nThis\nemployers\u2019 group, at its\nrecent regular membership\nmeeting in Cincinnati, approved\n'a resolution stating the associa\ntion's opposition to the Chamber\nof Commerce's scheme.\nJoining other clergymen in\nopposing the Chamber's proposal\nwas the Rev. Dr. John Bruere,\n'minister of Calvary Presbyterian\ni Church in Cleveland. He said,\nthe Chamber's proposal was \"dis\nhonest in its designation, un\nI workable and disruptive of our\neconomic system.\u201d\n1 Object to State Interference\nI\nThe Contractors Association,\nas a number of others have done,'\nindicated that it objected to state\nintervention in the free collec\ntive bargaining process.\n\u201cWe are of the opinion that a\nmore satisfactory solution to the\nmany problems inherent to the\nlathing and plastering industry\ncan, and have been solved by i\nnegotiations between two re\nsponsible groups, each recogniz\ning the others\u2019 problems and\nneeds,\u201d the Association stated.\ncrease in 33 states in March with\nthe national rate moving from\n7.5 to 7.8 percent.\nNine states had unemployment\nexceeding 10 percent, including\nMichigan with 14 percent and\nKentucky, West Virginia and\nMontana with more than 12 per\ncent. j\nNegroes Hit Hardest\nA separate Labor Dept, report\nshowed that Negro workers had\nbeen hit much harder by the re\ncession than white workers with\nthe non-white rate of unemploy\nment running 16 percent com\npared to 7 for white workers.\nJ\n1\nThe report noted also that\nabout half of the nation's job- i\nless in February were married\nmen.\nThe deepening of the recession\nreflected in the unemployment\nfigures showed up in other re\nports also. 1\nSteel output, down to 48.6\nMore Layoffs9 Temporary\nPlant Shutdowns Hit Area\nA continued rise in layoffs and an increase in tem\nporary plant shutdowns in the Toledo area refuted rosy\nstatements from the Eisenhower Administration that the\nend of the recession was in sight.\nA spot survey by the Union Journal disclosed that lay\noffs in Toledo plants were\ncontinuing, and along with it\nwas a greater increase in\nplant shutdowns for one week\nor more.\nScheduled to shut down for\none week beginning Monday\nwere Toledo's Auto-Late plants.\nThe work force there already\nhad been reduced to 1,500 from\na total of about 4,200 which pre\nvailed over a year ago.\nShut down a week ago for \u201cin\nventory adjustments,\u201d lack of\nbusiness and other reasons were\nWillys Motors, Toledo Pipe\nThreading, Chevrolet and Cham\npion Spark Plug, which was out\nfor four days.\nNo Signs of Pickup\nAn official at the Toledo of\nfice, Bureau of Unemployment\nCompensation said he had\nchecked area manufacturing\nplants for any signs of a pickup\nand had been unable to find any.\nNew Unemployment Compen\nsation claims totaled 4,327 last\nweek and continuing claims\nstood at 10,997. An upsurge in\nclaimants exhausting jobless\nbenefits was expected this month\nwith the situation growing stead\nily worse unless employment\npicked up, the Toledo BUC said.\nI No great increase in Building\nTrades employment was seen de\n'spite the improved weather, and\nThe Association also recog\nnized the fact that the Ohio\nChamber\u2019s campaign to outlaw\nthe union shop would seriously\nweaken Organized Labor's abil\nity to win decent wages and\nworking conditions for its mem\nbers.\nTo eliminate or \u201csubstantially\nweaken labor's right to bargain\ncollectively, would be similar to\nclosing all of the banks in the\ncountry because a teller or a\nbank president absconded with\nsome of the funds,\u201d the Associa\ntion added.\nWould Destroy Principle\nThe Rev, Bruere said that\nwhatever the intention of the\n\u201cright-to-work\u201d law, its effect\nwould be to destroy the principle\nof collective bargaining.\u201d\n\u201cThe average employer wants\na good and responsible union to\ndeal with, not a disorganized\nmelee of individuals and small\ngroups, unable to agree among\nthemselves,\u201d he said.\nThe proposed \u201cright-to-work\u201d\namendment also has been con\ndemned in recent statements by\nthe Catholic Bishops of Ohio and\nRabbi Abba H. Silver of the\nTemple in Cleveland.\npercent of capacity in the first\nweek of April\u2014a nine-year low\n\u2014was expected to drop even\nlower to 48.4 percent in the sec\nond week.\nThe auto industry reported\nadditional shutdowns and lay\noffs. March auto production\nregistered 357,049 cars com\npared to 578,356 in March\n1957.\nA study by the National In\ndustrial Conference Board\nshowed that payrolls shrank by\nan estimated $1.5 billion in the\nfirst seven months of the reces\nsion with only 30 percent of the\nloss in wages and salaries off\nset by unemployment benefits.\nIn addition to the unemploy\nment benefits provided by the\nfederal-state system, an estimat\ned $25 million in union-negotiat\ned supplemental employment\nbenefits in the auto and steel in\ndustries have been paid out since\nthe onset of the recession.\na rise in employment in ship\nping and coal loading was de\nferred because of the delay in\nthe shipping season until May 1.\nLack of demand was given as the\nreason for the postponement.\nAdding to the gloomy picture\nwas the halt in operations at\nBliss Foundry April 1 idling 75\nworkers and a report by the E.\nW. Bliss Co. that it will suspend\noperations at the Toledo Machine\nTool division May 2 for an\nindefinite period.\nSeveral Toledo plants report\ned continuing layoffs which\nswelled manufacturing u n e m\nployment ranks.\nLIBBEY-OWENS-FORD union\nofficials said 47 more workers\nwere to be laid off this week\ncutting their normal work force\nof 5,200 by 1,700.\nKENT-OWENS which manu.\nfactures machine tools continued\nlopping the work force leaving\n60 on the job out of a regular\ncomplement of 180.\nDOEHLER-JARVIS idled 60\nto 70 more Wednesday leaving\nonly 1800 working out of a to\nUl of 2.800.\nAt CHEVROLET only 800\nwere working out of a total of\nmore than 1,800.\nHigher Court\nAlso States\nSUB Legal\nThe Ohio Seventh District Ap\npeals Court upheld a ruling by a\nYoungstown Common Pleas\nJudge that Supplemental Unem\nployment Benefit payments are\nlegal and do not conflict with the\nState Unemployment Compensa\ntion law.\nThe ruling was handed down\nWednesday and an entry made\ngiving the state 20 days to ap\npeal to the Ohio Supreme Court.\nUAW Vice President Richard\nGosser and Region 2-B Director\nCharles Ballard both hailed the\ndecision and called upon Gov.\nC. William O\u2019Neill to abide by\nthe decision and permit the pay\nments of SUB which had been\nlegally negotiated between\nunions and management.\n\u201cAllowing the payments now,\u201d\nthey said, \u201cwill give a much\nneeded boost to purchasing pow\ner to workers who have been\nidled through no fault of theirs.\n\u201cSuch an increase in purchas\ning power, to which they are en\ntitled by labor contract, will en\nable the unemployed who are so\nprotected to meet needed bills\nand give their families a higher\nstandard of living which they\ncan now afford. It will also help\nmerchants in communities\nthroughout Ohio and thus serve\nas a shot in the arm in this re\ncession period.\u201d\na\nThe Ohio CIO recently made\nsurvey showing that 90,000\nworkers are entitled to SUB pay\nments in the state and these\nwould total $1 million a week.\nPlease DO NOT Patronize Lasalle\n\u2018s","height":"26676","width":"19424"}}
